🟢 Language ➡ C
🟢 Topic ➡ Date type

🧠 Data Types in C
Data types define the type and size of data a variable can hold. They are categorized into:

1️⃣ Basic Data Types
These are the fundamental types built into C.

🔹 int — Integer
💾 Size: Typically 4 bytes
🧮 Example:
int age = 30;

🔹 float — Single-precision Floating Point
💾 Size: Typically 4 bytes
💸 Example:
float salary = 50000.50;


🔹 double — Double-precision Floating Point
💾 Size: Typically 8 bytes
🧪 Example:
double pi = 3.14159;


🔹 char — Character
💾 Size: 1 byte
🔠 Range: -128 to 127 (or 0 to 255 for unsigned char)
📝 Example:
char initial = 'A';


2️⃣ Derived Data Types
Built using basic data types.

🔸 array[] — Collection of Same Type
📦 Example:
int numbers[10];


🔸 *pointer — Memory Address of a Variable
🎯 Example:
int *ptr;


🔸 struct — Grouping Different Data Types
📋 Example:
struct Person {
    char name[50];
    int age;
};


🔸 union — Shared Memory Space for All Members
🧳 Example:
union Data {
    int intValue;
    float floatValue;
    char charValue;
};


🔸 enum — Named Integer Constants
📆 Example:
enum Weekday { Sunday, Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday, Friday, Saturday };


3️⃣ Void Type
🔸 void — No Return or Parameters
🚫 Used when no value is returned or passed.

📣 Example:
void displayMessage() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
}


4️⃣ Type Modifiers
Used to alter the range or size of basic data types.

🔣 Modifier	              🧾 Meaning                  	🧪 Example
signed	    Allows positive and negative values	           signed int a = -10;
unsigned	Only positive values	                       unsigned int b = 20;
short     	Smaller range, saves memory	                   short int c = 32767;
long	    Extended range	                               long int d = 1234567890;
long        long	Larger than long, used in C99+         long long int e = 1234567890123456789LL;
